@NODE "Mail.12" "Re: vwait"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 1998 22:06:15 -0500
Subject: Re: vwait

Hi Paul

On 17-Jul-98, Paul West wrote:
> hi
> 
> why does VWait seem to take so much time?
> 

Vwait will stop the program flow until the next Vblank interrupt, but this is
only 1/50th second in PAL or 1/60th second in NTSC at the most.

It is probably the code that comes before it that is slowing things down.  Or
if you have the debugger turned on things will be very slow...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.13" "Re: vwait"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 1998 20:00:15 -0500
Subject: Re: vwait

Hi Paul,

On 18-Jul-98, Paul West wrote:

> Normally I am able to do a certain amount of processing without vwaits
> in one continuous loop. Lets say I blit 120 32x32 shapes and the
> routine runs at almost exactly 25fps (just over) without a vwait. If I
> then add a vwait, I am only able to run at 25fps if I take out 20 blit
> operations!
> 
> The first vwait to be executed should synchronise the routine to the
> display, as the routine normally runs at 25fps without vwait. Then the
> routine should be running and ending just prior to the point where the
> next vwait would be ideally necessary. And yet, doing the vwait
> gobbles up the amount of cpu time in which I could be doing 20 blits.
> 
> I would like to know also if it is illegal or dangerous to put the
> ENTIRE blitz program into a verticle blank interrupt. Any idea?

Well, if it is in Blitz mode the only restrictions are that no strings may be
accessed, and that it must always execute in 1 Vblank or less.

In Amiga mode, no blitter, Intuition, or file access commands can be used
either.

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.14" "Re: vwait"
 Sat, 18 Jul 1998 20:04:52 +0100 (BST)
 <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sat, 18 Jul 1998 11:20:09 -0500 (CDT)
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 1998 11:17:57 +0500
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Subject: Re: vwait

On 18-Jul-98, Paul West flashed:
>hi

>why does VWait seem to take so much time?


  VWait waits for the next vertical blank (repositioning of the raster
to the top of the screen) and your program does absolutly nothing while
it is waiting.  It should only be used for timing a program and then
only after everything you want to do in the current cycle is complete.


cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)





@ENDNODE
