@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.17" "Re: vwait"
 18 Jul 1998 21:51:43 +0100 (BST)
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 1998 05:46:31 +0000
From: Paul West <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: vwait

Curt

> It is probably the code that comes before it that is slowing things down.  Or
> if you have the debugger turned on things will be very slow...

No I know what I'm talking about, vwait is slow.

Normally I am able to do a certain amount of processing without vwaits
in one continuous loop. Lets say I blit 120 32x32 shapes and the
routine runs at almost exactly 25fps (just over) without a vwait. If I
then add a vwait, I am only able to run at 25fps if I take out 20 blit
operations!

The first vwait to be executed should synchronise the routine to the
display, as the routine normally runs at 25fps without vwait. Then the
routine should be running and ending just prior to the point where the
next vwait would be ideally necessary. And yet, doing the vwait
gobbles up the amount of cpu time in which I could be doing 20 blits.

I would like to know also if it is illegal or dangerous to put the
ENTIRE blitz program into a verticle blank interrupt. Any idea?

--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.18" "Re: void"
	(envelope-from rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    24 Jul 98 12:51:34 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 12:51:27 +0100
Subject: Re: void

It seems to me (from the autodocs) that you need to pass the 
result of RTGOpenFont to RTGSetFont. i.e.

font.l = RTGOpenFont(*myRTGScreen, *myTextAttr)
; *myTextAttr needs to be filled in and I don't know about
; *myRTGScreen but it probably does
RTGSetFont(*myRTGScreen, font)

 Apologies if this is what you have already done.


.oO_David_McMinn_Oo.
|rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk|



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.19" "Re: void"
	(envelope-from rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    24 Jul 98 12:13:39 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 12:13:34 +0100
Subject: Re: void

On 24 Jul 98, at 4:09, Peter Thor gave this nugget of information:

> Example, i wanna give a function a pointer to something, though it seems
> like that pointer is private and should NOT be passed, instead when I look
> into the syntax for how it is done in its original form (c code) is uses a
> void instead of a pointer.

 If you mean it uses a (look away if you hate C):

	void *blah

instead of a:

	struct <something> *blah

then the void is uses to represent a generic pointer to data. i.e. it is 
simply an address of some data rather than representing a 
structure or variable (although it may be taken as such within the 
function).
 To do this in blitz simply pass the address.


.oO_David_McMinn_Oo.
|rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk|



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.20" "Re: void"
          Fri, 24 Jul 1998 13:30:52 +0200 (MET DST)
From: Peter Thor <thor@mailbox.swipnet.se>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 13:28:38 -0500
Subject: Re: void

The 24-Jul-98, David McMinn wrote:

>> It only uses a:
>> 
>> void *
>> 
>> Yes, no pointerholder what so ever.

> Is this in the function prototype or definition (actual code)? Could 
>you send me the line?

*Synopsis*
RtgSetFont(RtgScreen, font)

void RtgSetFont(struct RtgScreen *, void *)

*Inputs*
RtgScreen - an RtgScreen
font - a font pointer. The structure of it is PRIVATE to rtgmaster.library
(and not the same for all sublibraries...)

IF i supply the pointer of a previoulsy opened font it produces a guru, if i
supply something else, like a zero of a blank pointer it guru's.

It seems like the pointer of the font is being hold in memory and taken out
WHEN you use the RtgSetFont after RtgLoadFont.

//Thor
