@NODE "Mail.49" "System fonts & more"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 07 Jul 1998 05:51:15 -0500
Subject: System fonts & more

Hi Blitzwing

On 04-Jul-98, Blitzwing wrote:
> On 02-Jul-98, Curt Esser wrote:
>> Hi Blitzwing
> 
>> I tried to send some stuff to you, but the email was bounced back  (twice!)
> 
> Sorry Curt dunno if this is what you've got
> 
> blitzwing@goldweb.com.au

Yes, but the email comes back saying "access denied" ??
> 
> A few other things I'd like to look into is executing dos statements 

> It's something like      Execute_

Yes, it is "Execute_ command$,0,0"

I'm not sure what the 0,0 is for, but it is necessary.
> 
> but if you could just show me how to a) open a CLI   b)do a directory
listing
> and c) something that passes arguements (say lha) I can work the rest out
> myself.

Well, the command itself doesn't open a CLI.  Rather, it allows you to issue a
command as if you were typing it into a CLI that was already open.  Just like
using the WorkBench "Execute Command" menu item.

I tried using it for doing a directory listing, but it just sends it to
Blitz's CLI, and then it disappears instantly - not much use...

There is an example on my web site for reading a directory listing into a
string array if that would help.

It looks like you are trying to do some archiving/de-archiving stuff?

You could get the file name(s) using an asl requester, then use execute to
call .lha like this:

command$="sys:c/lha (lha arguments here)"
Execute_ command$,0,0

Using it this way will cause your program to wait until the other program has
finished.  If you want the other program to "detach" so you program can
continue, add the Run command like this:

Execute_ "Run >NIL: SYS:Utilities Multiview docs/MyGuide",0,0

This would open multiview with MyGuide loaded, but allow the main program to
continue.

Also, you might want to get the program "MADS" by Alvaro Thompson from Aminet.
 It is an Arc/Unarc utility written in Blitz, and has the source with it.  It
uses BSS, so some commands won't tokenize for you, but it will give you some
ideas anyway.  
> 
> Also someone pointed out something like a textlen_ function for getting the
> width of a font....

This one really tells you the width, in pixels, that a specified string would
require if printed in the current window font.  Unless you are using a
fixed-width font, there really is no set character width.

For example:

t$="Just a test"
pixels.w=TextLength_(RastPort(0),&t$,Len(t$)

The variable pixels now shows the length t$ would use if printed in the
current font of Window 0.  (Of course there MUST be a window 0 open first)

There is also a command "TextFit_" which does this in reverse.  It will tell
you how many characters of the string would fit into a specified space.

For an example of this get the text reader file on my web page.

 
>any ideas what libs I'd need to any / all of the above
or
> am I fairly well covered in most areas ?

No special libs needed for any of this.  In fact, any command with a "_" at
the end is using a standard Amiga system lib, not a Blitz lib.

> P.S one other thing I never mentioned (I think), is the fact I live is
> Australia and getting hold of s/ware is hard here at the moment, I'm a P5
> dealer and can barely get things moving. So if you know of someone downunder
> who's got the blitz suite etc / of upgrades of sorts, could you put me in
> contact with them or them in contact with me. I love this machine but it's
so
> bloody hard when you can't get any local help. 

Yes, I know the feeling!  I am in the USA, and local shops have no idea even
what an Amiga is.  Hopefully, Gateway will soon change this.

The only place I know that has BSS is GuildHall in the UK.  And I have never
been able to contact them myself...

The only other option is to find a copy of the Ultimate Blitz CD, which also
has it, from a local dealer.

I know TLAS software in the US has it - probably some dealer in your area too.

Later...
-- 
