@NODE "Mail.55" "Standard palette (save it)"
          Paris Mon, 27 Jul 1998 19:54:52 +0200 (MET DST)
          Paris Mon, 27 Jul 1998 19:54:49 +0200 (MET DST)
From: Mathias PARNAUDEAU <Mathias.P@wanadoo.fr>
Date: Mon, 27 Jul 1998 12:30:45 +0100
Subject: Standard palette (save it)

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.

This message was composed on an Amiga using the YAM mailer.
YAM is available at http://bitcom.ch/~mbeck/

--BOUNDARY.7512.2267.269526944.1

Hi all,

yesterday, I read a message about "Save a standard palette" (like PPaint,=
 not
like BlitzPalette). I forgot who wrote this (I deleted the mail, oops !) =
but
I'm attaching a source. Use it, it works ;-)

Bye,

                     Mathias

-- =

email       : Mathias.P@wanadoo.fr
site web : bient=F4t ...


--BOUNDARY.7512.2267.269526944.1

; Save a standard palette (PPaint palette)
; By   : Cyanure (Mathias.P@wanadoo.fr)
; Date : 26/07/98

Statement SavePaletteFile{NumberBmap.b,FileName.s}
  DEFTYPE .b NumberPlanes
  DEFTYPE .w NumberColors,FSize

  NumberPlanes=Peek.b(Addr BitMap(NumberBmap)+5)
  NumberColors=2^NumberPlanes
  FSize=3*NumberColors+48               ; File size

  If OpenFile(1,FileName.s)=-1
    *pf=AllocMem_(FSize,0)          ; Memory for the palette file
    *pf0=*pf                        ; Beginning of the palette file
                                      address
    Poke.l *pf,$464f524d            ; FORM
    Poke.l *pf+4,FSize-8            ;
    Poke.l *pf+8,$494c424d          ; ILBM
    Poke.l *pf+12,$424d4844         ; BMHD
    Poke.l *pf+16,20                ; Size of the BMHD chunk
    Poke.l *pf+20,0                 ; width and height
    Poke.l *pf+24,0                 ; x and y
    Poke.l *pf+28,$03020180         ; I don't know why but it works !
    Poke.l *pf+32,0                 ; transparency and aspect
    Poke.l *pf+36,0                 ; page width and page height
    Poke.l *pf+40,$434d4150         ; CMAP
    Poke.l *pf+44,NumberColors*3    ; Size of the CMAP chunk

    *pf+48                          ; Increases the pointer

    For c=0 To NumberColors-1
      Poke.b *pf,AGARed(c)
      Poke.b *pf+1,AGAGreen(c)
      Poke.b *pf+2,AGABlue(c)
      *pf+3
    Next c

    WriteMem 1,*pf0,FSize            ; Writes in file #1
    FreeMem_ *pf0,FSize
    CloseFile 1

  EndIf

End Statement

.main

WBStartup
NoCli

; I suppose the palette you want to save is one of an open bitmap
; So, I open such a bitmap :
Screen 0,0,0,320,256,8,0,"title",1,2
ScreensBitMap 0,0
LoadBitMap 0,"images:iff/ofs.iff",0   ; chooses a bitmap
LoadPalette 0,"images:iff/ofs.iff"
Use Palette 0

SavePaletteFile{0,"ram:PaletteStd.col"}

End





--BOUNDARY.7512.2267.269526944.1--





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.56" "Sprite Problems"
    10 Jul 98 09:06:20 +0000
From: "Dalai" <A1JONATH@doreen.rainhammark.kent.sch.uk>
Date:          Fri, 10 Jul 1998 09:05:50 GMT
Subject:       Sprite Problems

Hello,
    I am using the Display Library commands in a game I am writing, and
to get the mouse pointer on the screen, I use the following:

SetInt 5
  DisplaySprite 0,MouseX,MouseY,0   (I think)
End SetInt

This works fine, but occasionally, when I move the mouse pointer quickly
from the bottom of the screen to the top the pointer becomes a long thin
column of garbledness. Freaky, eh?

Dalai.



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.57" "Re: Sprite Problems"
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 1998 11:36:09 +0200
From: Manfred Linzner <Manfred.Linzner@munich.netsurf.de>
Subject: Re: Sprite Problems

> 
> Hello,
>     I am using the Display Library commands in a game I am writing, and
> to get the mouse pointer on the screen, I use the following:
> 
> SetInt 5
>   DisplaySprite 0,MouseX,MouseY,0   (I think)
> End SetInt
> 
> This works fine, but occasionally, when I move the mouse pointer quickly
> from the bottom of the screen to the top the pointer becomes a long thin
> column of garbledness. Freaky, eh?
> 

The vertical interrupt has not the highest priority. Other interrupts
like the
CIA or other Vertical-Blank interrupts can cause some delay before the
DisplaySprite command sets the new values into the copperlist. This
could
cause BB2 to change the copperlist spritepos while the Copper is reading
it
-> Trashed Sprites

You could avoid that prob in most cases by disabling the system.
Or try to set a 
Vwaitpos 255
before your displaysprite command.

-- 
-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+
 Manfred.Linzner@munich.netsurf.de aka Pink/aBYSS
http://homepages.munich.netsurf.de/Manfred.Linzner/
           http://ABYSS.HOME.ML.ORG
-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+*-*+




@ENDNODE
