@NODE "Mail.59" "Setting menu and window colours"
 18 Jul 1998 20:59:56 +0100 (BST)
 18 Jul 1998 20:57:30 +0100
 18 Jul 1998 20:57:19 +0100
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 1998 20:57:13 +0100
From: Dermot Smyth <D.P.Smyth@sheffield.ac.uk>
Subject: Setting menu and window colours

Another message from blitz-list's resident oaf.....

Hi,

I am doing an editor for my game and I will be loading in
the game palette into the editor but obviously I don't want to
use the game palettes colours for the menus,windows etc...
because the colours won`t be suited.

I've been trying to select my own colours for 
the menu bar,menu text,menu highlight and
also window boxes and text.

Unfortunately I am having trouble achieving this!

I have tried setting Dpen and Bpen on both screen
and window commands but I don't think it is doing
it right, also this does not include the colour for the
menu bar itself.

Does anyone know which colour registers the menu bar,
menu text, menu highlight, window box,window text want 
to use?

Can anyone explain the Dpen, Bpen variables better than
the crap manual?

As ever I'm in total confusion.

>>>ALEX<<< Smyth 




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.60" "Re: Setting menu and window colours"
          Tue, 21 Jul 1998 00:50:31 +0200 (MET DST)
From: Peter Thor <thor@mailbox.swipnet.se>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 1998 00:38:35 -0500
Subject: Re: Setting menu and window colours

The 18-Jul-98, Dermot Smyth wrote:
  
>Does anyone know which colour registers the menu bar,
>menu text, menu highlight, window box,window text want 
>to use?
 
I belive intuition locks up register 0-9, though you can use other colours if
you like. 
 
What you could look at are the two commands *BorderPens* and *GadgetPens*.
They will alter the colours of gadgets and so on created from Blitz internal
Gadgetcommands.

But to change the colours of menus and requestors etc. you need to use the
*ScreenPens* command. Use *ScreenPens* before opening the screen.
For example:

  *ScreenPens* 1,2,1,3,1,0,2

The colours can have values like this, though they're freely chosen by
yourself:

  *RGB* 0,10,10,10   ;grey shell
  *RGB* 1,0,0,0          ;used as text AND gadgetborder- black
  *RGB* 2,15,15,15  ;used as gadgetborder - white
  *RGB* 3,3,3,10       ;blue colour for selected files and gadgets

This was a very easy example, feel free to experiment with the values.

Regards.
//Thor
-- 
Peter Thor, Coder Asm/Blitz/C/C++
