@NODE "Mail.62" "Re: sections AND gfx"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 1998 18:24:02 -0500
Subject: Re: sections AND gfx

Hi David

On 20-Jul-98, David McMinn wrote:

>> The problem is that the code wants to have a `chip section', ie a
> 
>> section of the program that will be loaded into chipram, and it
> 
>> accesses the location of this data by way of a label.
> 
>> I take it blitz is not able to do sections in this way?
> 
>> If not, how could I do it so that I could reserve a memory bank and
> 
>> then have it located at a particular label? I have a grave feeling it 
>> is
> 
>> not at all possible.

A label is used to "point" to a section of memory where some data is stored. 
I think you could probably substitute a pointer, in this case pointing to your
chip ram bank.

The chip ram code itself would need to be assembled ahead of time, then loaded
into the bank at run time.  Or if it is just some data, you could "poke" it
into the bank from your exec.



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
