</color> This may sound like a hassle, but if you can assemble (using a 
real assembler) the code that has to be in chip, then at program 
startup allocate some chip memory and read from the output file of 
the assembler into the memory, then you can call it by jumping to 
the address of the memory block. If you don't have a real 
assembler, then you could always look up a 68k reference book 
and hard code the machine code values into data statements :)


<color><param>7F00,0000,0000</param>> also, how could I gain access to the graphics library base address and

> have it located at a label within the program?


<color><param>0000,0000,0000</param> Theres a command in Elmore libs for finding the base of the 
graphics library (GraphicsLibBase or something). Alternatively, you 
could search the exec list until you find graphics.library or open it 
again (as library is only loaded into memory once, so it will be 
there for sure).



<nofill>
