@NODE "Mail.66" "Re: Score display"
 Sun, 19 Jul 1998 08:38:43 +0100 (BST)
 <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sun,
 19 Jul 1998 08:36:09 +0100 (BST envelope-from tucks@pavilion.co.uk)
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 1998 19:59:53 +0100
From: Liz Tucker <tucks@pavilion.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Score display

Jake Frederick wrote:
> 
> The game I am making requires two displays on one screen, a scrolling
> playfield and score display. What is the best way to do this in an OS
> friendly
> way? Should I put one on the screen and one in a window, both in a
> winow, or
> both on the screen?

I would probably use two screens. In fact I have played around with this
in C and Blitz but I have never been able to get a smooth scrolling
screen for my map display using the OS so if anyone can then please
tell me about it.

To get around the problem of the user screen switching and separating
your two screens you can tie them together by creating the second one
as a Child of the first. This is done using screen tags. I havent got
my C code to hand at the moment but if you want to know more then ask
again and I`ll look up what I did.
 
See you,

Liz.  
tucks@pavilion.co.uk

