@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.84" "Re: Program code creator very easy to use"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 25 Jul 98 14:53:21 +0000
Subject: Re: Program code creator very easy to use

Alex,

Your disgust at another's comments:

> You are a smug, ignorant bastard.
> 
> Just because something is easy for you doesn't mean it's
> easy for other people.
> 
> You should respect other people even if they are not
> at the same level you are at.
> 
> You give this list a bad name.

Now now! :)

What he sais is to an extent true. The more generalised you make
something the less efficient it becomes. There is nothing faster than
a hardcoded, ie custom-written routine crafted entirely to suit a
particular situation. As you experienced with the copy from fastram to
chipram that you tried to do. Using a general scroll routine you got
poor results but with a custom-written copy routine things were a lot
faster.

Some programmers are `programmers', you know, like they put themselves
in a little pocket, under the label, part of the programming culture,
really `into' it you know. And then there are those who are sort of
detatched and just don't really think there's any issue about stuff,
as yourself and myself.

I agree that a more generalised approach may help a large group of
people to get results faster. There are gui creators by the dozen for
various languages but mainly for creating intuition stuff. As it is,
blitz does a tremendous amount of work for the programmer. If you
don't know what it takes to code stuff in assembler at the lowest
level you don't appreciate how high-level blitz already is. The way
blitz handles intuition objects (screens and so on) and blitz mode
with only a few instructions is amazing considering how much work is
actually going on under the hood. I still find it amazing how easy it
is to open an intuition screen or set up a custom copperlist, the
kinds of things that was such hard work when I used to use AMOS.

In a sense, blitz is a step towards a visual programming environment,
in which certain groups of routines are represented with keywords, ie
tokens. Yes okay so its only a textfile essentially but it's by no
means at the lowest level. There aren't many steps further up that you
can go. As someone has suggested they're doing an `AmiVisual' visual
style of creating programs. There are things like those game creators
that you just have to use the mouse, and the dreaded ShootEmUp
Construction Kit. There is a big danger of these churning out sloppy
generalised code with lots of need to cover variability that isn't
needed in all cases. Depends how well the thing is done really. You'd
be surprised how relatively simple the building blocks of a game are,
and different types of games have a lot in common. Be is a shootemup
or a platformer there isn't much different between them anyway, so it
isn't always /creating/ generalisations but simple the fact that
things are quite alike anyway.

Personally I wouldn't mind using an even higher level environment. I
wouldn't mind there being a higher-level way of creating game graphics
either because it's so bloody painstaking but I can see no way of
doing that short of a connection to the brain. You know that tanks
game demo I sent you? Well almost all the code for that so far is for
the control panel only and it takes up about 20 screens of text in TED
in a high resolution. All the yacker just to implement a few ideas.
Trouble is that if there was a system to click on buttons and stuff to
do the same it might not let you do what you want to do. It might have
no way of letting you bring to life the ideas you have, that you could
do if you were coding at a lower level. I especially doubt it would do
optimisations, certainly not down to the assembler level like many
people like to do (me included).

I am not up for taking things to a higher level to the exclusion of
the flexibility of lower levels, which is what I think that other
geezer was saying. But having things at a higher level while maintaing
of even enhancing flexibility would be really tremendous. If I could
point to a little icon representing a variable that I can see
somewhere on the screen and drag and drop it into the current line I'm
working on that alone would save loads of typing. If there could be
`templates' for general engine types that would be really quick, like
a general framework of a fastram planar system, or of a fastram chunky
system, or a graphics card system, or an easy way of creating an
extension library as more of a compiler option than a way of having to
code things. If you could have levels of zoom so you could if you
wanted customise thing at a low level that would be cool, for every
instruction. There could be better ways of representing what's going
on in the program rather than just replacing words with pictures, like
a `goto' draws a little line linking to some other place. The program
doesn't even necessarily need to exist in a `top to bottom' fashion.

Anyway, enjoy and stop fretting about nothing.
:-0

--
Paul.

