@NODE "Mail.97" "Re: Packer"
From: "Tri" <scillo@geocities.com>
Subject: Re: Packer
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 1998 08:20:48 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"

To Dave et al,

Hey, man, Imploder is old and rubbish. Music modules comprise of 2 parts,
the block data and the samples. The block data is often mostly empty, so
compresses easily with Imploder or even Powerpacker. The sample-data,
however, is a different matter. Only a compression algorithm that is
specifically geared to compressing samples will achieve any kind of
impressive results. Your best bet is to get "ThePlayer6" from Aminet (do a
search, I can't remember where it is) then use the ASM replay code that
comes with it. This can automatically compress/decompress modules including
their sample data very nicely. However, I am too thick to use assembler, so
I don't use it. If you need the best "layman" compressor, get Stonecracker.
BSS from RWE has decompression routines in it. I haven't found Stonecracker
on the Aminet, however, and you might need to call a traditional PD library
to get hold of it. It is excellent, though, making a great job of graphics
and executables especially. I would post it on here, but it is Shareware and
I don't have the original docs.

BTW:  LHA is an ARCHIVER, and is not meant for this kind of on-the-fly use
at all, so forget it. Oh, and DecodeModule does allocate more memory. The
bonus of this is that you can decompress it from Fast-> Chip.

Nick Chapman / Skillo Software Interactive
scillo@mailexcite.com
http://www.bomb.demon.co.uk
