@NODE "Mail.130" "Re: NewLibrarySet V1.10"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 16 Jul 98 23:03:33 +0000
Subject: Re: NewLibrarySet V1.10

Fred,

>     The masking is only present in the NChunkyBlit command and is pretty easy
> (and slow BTW :-(). I move the shape byte per byte and check if the colour is
> 0 or not. If it's 0, I don't copy the byte to the chunky buffer. These
> routines was written pretty fast and I know that we could do it better. But
> the NChunkyBlock4 seems to be the fastest routine available.

I was wondering if it would be at all faster to just be inputting
twice as much data, ie that you have a mask in the same way that you
have one in planar masking.. with $FF if the pixel is set or $00 if
the pixel is free, then just do the usual ands and ors. ?
  
>     My config is an A1230/50, 16 Mb.

Are these results inclusive of conversion of chunky to planar?
 
>     ChunkyBuffer and shapes are in FAST memory ! I've take a 16*16 chunky
> block for all the testing. Maximum blit for 1 VWAit (Pal mode-50hz)
> 
>     NChunkyBlit  : 140 Blits (with transparent)
>     NChunkyBlock2: 310 Blits (no transparent)
>     NChunkyBlock4: 550 Blits (no transparent)

These are more or less exactly the results that I got in a little
test, while also doing c2p conversion. I have 040/25 and c2p takes
almost precicely 1 vwait, and 040/25 is about twice as fast as 030/50,
so that sounds about right.

--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
