@NODE "Mail.140" "Re: New User"
From: "Tri" <scillo@geocities.com>
Subject: Re: New User
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 1998 08:47:55 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"

On 30/6/98, Alastair Murray did blither thus:


>I've had blitz for quite some time but never used it much because I
>didn't really like it. It seemed to crash too much and most programs
>made with it were unreliable too.... plus the fact that the manual is
>appaling....

Yep, it's worse than bad. Half the commands are not in there, and the ones
that there are bring tears to the eyes of grown men. That manual is so bad,
it hurts.

>However, I've decided to give it a proper go now and am willing to be
>converted to it. Firstly though I have a few questions that I hope
>someone can help me with.

No problem, welcome to the party.

>1. I don't seem to be able to open a Hires Laced 256 colour screen
>(not intuition, for a game in blitz mode). Can this not be done?

Yes indeedy! Slices support interlace directly, but cannot do AGA. Coplists
do not support Interlace, so you have to do it yourself. It involves setting
up 2 bitmaps of normal height, then flicking between them at high speed.
They are at slightly differing verticle offsets, so that it looks like a
slightly flickery 25fps 512-line bitmap. I cannot remember how to do this,
though (it is the verticle offset bit...) but I might have some code lying
around. Unless someone else gets there first, I'll post it soon.

>2. What is the best version of TED and where can I get it? Most of
>them seem to crash all the time (including the SuperTED on AMINET).
>The one I'm using now is OK but a bit unfriendly. For example, AMIGA+I
>is not used for insert line.

The best is SuperTed version 2.5x. See (4). SuperTed in any form crashes for
me if I try any clever extras like the Calculator or IconDock. Switching all
of these off makes it stable as a rock, man. Is is while you are editing in
TED that you get crashes, or during you programmes? If it is the latter, TED
is not to blame, but buggy code ;-).

>3. Is there no clipping supported in the BBlit commands? If so, then
>what would someone reccomend to make a full scrolling game? Please
>don't say the "make a screen twice the size of the display" option
>because I don't really have the memory for that and besides, there
>should certainly be better options than that. If there is just a way
>of clipping BBlit then I would be fine from there on.

Well, there's the BitmapWindow command, but I can't make that work. Perhaps
the best bet is to ask Manfred Lizner or one of the other super-beings on
this list for their CPU-blit libs, which are now beginning to support
Clipping for all the family. What I have done is turned RunErrors off, and
used BBlit like normal. I bet this is generating loads of Enforcer hits and
memory-trashing, mind. Some folk reckon this will cause a crash, too.


>4. Extensions. I don't have anything except what came in the box of
>Blitz 2.1 Is there any updates? Where can I get them?

Try Guildhall Leisure in the UK. They distribute the BUM magazines (which
reached 10) which have extra libraries and code on them. The
BlitzSupportSuite which they also sell for about Ł15 is pretty much
essential these days. It comes with a whole goody-bag of well-documented
libraries, plus a new debugger, plus a map editor, plus a proper shapes
editor, plus...SuperTed 2.5x. It's great!
Also, try http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Pines/4814/BBLIBS.HTM for
some extras. Flicking though "dev/basic" on Aminet uncovers some goodies as
well.

Nick Chapman / Skillo Software Interactive
scillo@mailexcite.com
http://www.bomb.demon.co.uk




