@NODE "Mail.154" "my views"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 20 Jul 98 17:35:09 +0000
Subject: my views

Hi.

I just thought I'd add my few cents worth on a few things.

I think the idea of new manuals is a good one. Some of the commands in
the blitz manual have documentation which has nothing to do with the
command. DisplayAdjust for example. It's very vague. Certainly doesn't
live up to the standard of the old AMOS Pro manual.

Whoever does the manual is unimportant, and even having more than one
manual is a good idea as somebody said.. things will be presented
diffferently, different details, different approaches and examples and
so on. Good to have a number of angles of looking at it. I'd be
tempted to do a manual myself but I don't /actually/ know blitz all
that well.

It seems a number of people have been experimenting with blitting
using the CPU, wether it be chunky or planar, and an increasing number
of people are coming out of the woodwork requiring these things. Would
be nice to have one or two definitive systems for public usage. Dave
Newton is working on a very nice comprehensive system and I have been
working on something myself on and off.

Some people are also interested in moving to chunky graphics, c2p, and
graphics card support. Hopefully some definitive results will arise
for that direction shortly. I have been working on a c2p routine
myself, not my own code but just getting it to work in blitz. Should
have that available for you soon. I have just started writing a
chunky-based shootemup game so I may develop some other routines that
will be publically useable.

I think it might be nice to see new manuals in html with
pictures/diagrams as images can make grasping things a lot easier.
Nothing fancy, just something to get the point accross. Amigaguide is
certainly okay but it's a bit bland and navigation isn't really all
that hot. Could be nice to have a set of executable (as well as
sourcecode) example programs to run when something is clicked.

I wouldn't mind doing a few images for a manual, ie like diagrams or
representations of theory.

Umm.. that's about all I have to say.

--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
