@NODE "Mail.167" "Re: miscellaneous questions"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 1998 18:11:06 -0500
Subject: Re: miscellaneous questions

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1747816184.1

Hi Philippe

On 19-Jul-98, Philippe Bovier wrote:
> Hello,

> - De-Archiveur is programmed in Blitz Mode and It used Shapes for his GUI.

It is not a good idea to program a utility such as this in Blitz mode.  Blitz
mode disables the system, and no multi-tasking is possible.

> We  have  no  idea to use the same shape than the one used in De-Archiveur
> (bitz mode) in XFD PATCH GUI (system mode).  How can we used a shape in a
> program in system mode ?????  (little source welcome if possible).

Are you using the shapes as gadgets?  Or just as screen graphics?  If they are
gadgets, you can use the GTshapegadget commands - or the standard ShapeGadgets
if you need more than 4 colours.  If they are only for screen graphics, you
can use Wblit to put them where you want in your window.

> How can we used a screenrequester to choose a screen mode and how can we
> adapt the GUI with all the differents modes available ??? (Filefrog is
> completely programmed in system mode).

I have attached an example of a screenmode requester.  To adapt your program
to look correct on all screenmodes would be quite a difficult thing.

We designed our BeatBox2 program to fill a standard 640x400 or 640x512 screen,
then added a screenmode requester to allow different overscan sizes, GFX card
modes, etc. to be used.  Although the actual GUI doesn't change, we did make
it center itself on the selected screen, and allow for a limited range of user
font selection (8-15 points).  This provides a little flexibility, and even
this was fairly complicated.

You might consider using MUI or Triton if you want a great range of acceptable
sceeen sizes.

> - How much colors can I take in the Dpaint palette to transform some gfx
> in sprite (principal hero, shoot or options) to gain some speed ???

Sprites can be either in 3 or 15 colours  (15 colours uses 2 sprite channels
for the sprite)
> 
> - There is special place in the Dpaint palette for the sprite colors??

No, the sprite colours come from certain colour registers on the screen being
used. This depends on which sprite channel the sprite is displayed on.  See
the manual for the registers, etc.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


