@NODE "Mail.177" "Maths problem"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 29 Jul 98 19:36:03 +0000
Subject: Maths problem

Hi.

Somebody has recently requested information on a maths problem of how
to do software lines. There has already been a suggestion of how to
do it with floating point numbers but there is a much more efficient
and elegant integer method based on the Bresenhams algorithm for
scaling.

I wrote a somewhat lengthy and instructive text about the entire
topic, from the theory itself to sourcecode (pseudocode) to actually
draw a line, to how to implement it for scaling of bitmaps, rotation,
and some other nice things. It is only lucky that I wrote it on the
old A500 and therefore was able to find it lurking on a floppy disk.

I have uploaded the text to:

http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk/Lhas/Eoin.lha

or the page on which it can be downloaded is:

http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk/blitzprogramming.html

I could have attatched it here but it's 25k lha archive (>60k text)
and besides, it will get more hits for my website ;-)

If the text doesn't appear to be there yet, give it 24hours.

I can explain how the method works if you get stuck or find it
difficult to comprehend. The way that it works is based on a kind of
wraparound effect that occurs now and then in such a lovely way that
you are scaling one larger distance (Y for example, which is a
loopcounter) into a smaller one (X for example, which is only
incremented when there is wrap). It might sound confusing. It works
and it does not use any floating point.

I reccommend going to the above website/file and reading the text as
it goes into much more depth and gives many examples to take you
through.

In essense, the following is pseudocode to draw a line (between North
and NorthEast). I have removed some parts of the routine that I
considered not necessary as they are for aesthetics mainly.

; Coordinates
X1=6
Y1=9
X2=20
Y2=27
; Setup some variables
Count=1
XDiff=X2-X1
YDiff=Y2-Y1
; Simplify XDiff and YDiff
Finished=False
Repeat
   If (XDiff mod 2=0) and (YDiff mod 2=0) Then
      XDiff=XDiff/2
      YDiff=YDiff/2
   Else
      Finished=True
   EndIf
Until Finished=True
; Draw the line
X=X1
For Y=Y1 to Y2
   Count=Count+XDiff
   If Count>YDiff
      Count=Count-YDiff
      X=X+1
   EndIf
   Plot X,Y
Next Y

The following is the original Pascal sourcecode.

Procedure LineBres (Xa,Ya,Xb,Yb : Integer);
Var
   Dx,Dy,X,Y,XEnd,P : Integer;
Begin
   Dx=Abs(Xa-Xb);
   Dy=Abs(Ya-Yb);
   P=(2*Dy)-Dx;       { This is the bit i cut out and replaced with Cnt=1 }
   { Determine which point to use as start, which as end }
   If xa>xb Then
      Begin
         X=Xb;
         Y=Yb;
         XEnd=Xa;
      End
   Else
      Begin
         X=Xa;
         Y=Ya;
         XEnd=Xb;
      End;
   SetPixel(X,Y,1);  { plot }
   While X<XEnd do
      Begin
         X=X+1;
         If P<0 then P=P+(2*Y)   { Removed this }
         Else
            Begin
            Y=Y+1;
            P=P+(2*(Dy-Dx))      { Removed this also }
         End;
         SetPixel(X,Y,1)
      End;
End; { procedure }

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.178" "managing CRM datafiles"
	via sendmail with P\:smtp/R:inet_hosts/T:smtp
	id <m0ysJi5-00129GC@amauta.rcp.net.pe>
	for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sat, 4 Jul 1998 00:14:01 -0400 (EDT)
	(Smail-3.2.0.96 1997-Jun-2 #4 built 1997-Nov-6)
From: Mr.Byte/TEG <mrbyte@chavin.rcp.net.pe>
Date: Fri, 03 Jul 1998 23:59:39 -0500
Subject: managing CRM datafiles

> I`ve been trying to archive some files then decrunch them in my program.
> I`ve been testing the implode and deplode commands that came with blitz,
> they seem quick but doesn`t reduce the file size very much
 
> You could try using the Blitz crunchmania commands since they 
> provide reasonably slow crunching, reasonably fast decrunching
> and reasonably good compression :)
> I think the commands are called crmcrunch & Crmdecrunch. If
> they don't work have a look in your docs :)

In my game Gunbee F99, I use Blitz's Crunchmania commands and they work
perfectly, as also Bank commands for storing the address locations of
decoded objects, to later deallocation.

Anyway is not as simple as "load the data, decrunch it and decoded it".
I had to write a group of functions to load and manage correctly the
CRM crunched files, as also de/allocating required memory for decrunching,
decoding the objects, storing its information (lenght bytes, memory location,
because Decode commands don't reserve a memory chunk for the new object), etc.

It is not optimized, but anyway is working, easy to use and free of errors :)
If someone need it, I can send my Functions to manage Crunchmania files.

Ps: ...and may be someone of you can take a look and improve it?

