@NODE "Mail.205" "Interleaved BitMaps & Cookie Cut Blitting?"
	Wed, 22 Jul 1998 16:12:47 -0600 (CST)
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 1998 16:12:47 -0600 (CST)
From: Carlos Villarroel Cortes <carlosv@redes.unam.mx>
Subject: Interleaved BitMaps & Cookie Cut Blitting?

Well, i know that Blitz2 BITMAP objects support interleaved bitmaps. But=20
how i can declare an interleaved bitmap to allocate the correct memory and=
=20
BPL pointers with standard blitz commands?

So interleaved bitmaps permit to blit (block style) in one single pass,=20
telling to the blitter what to do and freeing up the CPU. (That is: true=20
paralell work CPU-Blitter in Blitz!). But how about cookie blitting??

Some one out there knows how to make a cookiecut blit without using a cooki=
e
image as big as the image itself?

Thanks everyone in advance. (it=B4s a very cool list)



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.206" "Re: Interleaved BitMaps & Cookie Cut Blitting?"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 22 Jul 98 22:40:50 +0000
Subject: Re: Interleaved BitMaps & Cookie Cut Blitting?

> Well, i know that Blitz2 BITMAP objects support interleaved bitmaps. But 
> how i can declare an interleaved bitmap to allocate the correct memory and 
> BPL pointers with standard blitz commands?

Use ScreenTags and use the #leaved (or similar) tag.
 
> So interleaved bitmaps permit to blit (block style) in one single pass, 
> telling to the blitter what to do and freeing up the CPU. (That is: true 
> paralell work CPU-Blitter in Blitz!). But how about cookie blitting??

Take a look at queues and QBlit. It is supposed to form a que of
blitter jobs to be done and in theory should zip through all your cals
to it and then go away and do the work while handing over control to
the main program. But I am not sure they implemented it that way.
 
> Some one out there knows how to make a cookiecut blit without using a cookie
> image as big as the image itself?

You'll need to use a custom blitmode, ie minterm, to use only the
cookiecut and to write it instead of using it as a mask. I am not sure
that it is possible to mask the mask however.

> 
> Thanks everyone in advance. (it´s a very cool list)

--
Paul.

