@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.231" "Re: Games on gfx-boards"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 09 Jul 1998 15:53:17 -0500
Subject: Re: Games on gfx-boards

Hi Andreas,

On 09-Jul-98, Andreas Etzrodt wrote:
> Hello,
> 
> I want to write a game. This game has to work on gfx-boards, too.
> But I don't have any experience in programming games or at least
> do some gfx-stuff with blitz basic. 
> 
> At the moment I open a screen with a taglist. Then I load an
> iff-image into a bitmap and copy it with bitmaptowindow to my
> screen (of course there is a window on this screen) as a
> backdrop-picture.

This should work OK on a GFX card (I am told) ^^^^

The problem will be with non-gfx card systems, bitmaptowindow will work also,
but it is VERY slow.

Probably better to set a variable to show if a gfx card is being used.
If it is, use BitMapToWindow to change images.  If not, use ShowBitmap
instead. 
> 
> This works fine. Now I want to use something like sprites/bobs/shapes
> wich I can control with a joypad. Which commands do I need to use?

To preserve the background, you will need to use the buffer-blitting
commands(Bblit, UnBuffer, etc.)
Or the Qblitting commands, with the optional 3rd bitmap for "erasing" the
blits.

Have a look at these in the manual.

For a full example, you will find the complete source for my Crazy 8's card
game on my web page.  This has loads of comments, and shows using
buffer-blits, double-buffering, etc. in Amiga mode.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
