@NODE "Mail.241" "Re: Gadgets"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 1998 18:41:22 -0500
Subject: Re: Gadgets

Hi Everyone,

On 20-Jul-98, Centro Amiga wrote:
> 
>> Its not so much the development time you have to think about, but returning
>> to the code months later for bug fixes etc. It's up to the individual I
>> suppose, but it's good practice to use constants instead of the values.
> 
> Not to mention that using IDCMP_xxxxxx will prevent you from
> waiting for $40 when you really meant $400 ;-)

Yes, this is all good advice.  But, the problem is (for me, anyway) just where
the !@?*#! do you find these constant names?  My manual only shows the hex
values, so these are what I've always used.  And for me, it is easier to
remember "$20 is gadget pressed" than to remember if it is spelled
"IDCMP_GadgetDown", "IDCMP_GADGETDOWN", "IDCMP_Gadgetdown", or whatever.  And
I usually do it like this in my code anyway:

if ev=$20     ;gadget pressed down

Someone once told me "If a program is properly commented, a competent
programmer in any language should be able to duplicate the program just from
the comments"

Later...
