@NODE "Mail.244" "Gadgets"
Date: 25 Jul 98 17:05:39 GMT
X-Plug: Xenolink, No. 1 BBS Software for the Amiga!
From: bml@darkside.demon.co.uk (Simon Archer)
Subject: Gadgets

On 20 Jul 98 Curt Esser wrote about 'Gadgets'.

 CE> Yes, this is all good advice.  But, the problem is (for me, anyway)
 CE> just where do you find these constant names?  My manual only shows the

OK, a list is provided:

#IDCMP_SIZEVERIFY    = $00000001
#IDCMP_NEWSIZE       = $00000002
#IDCMP_REFRESHWINDOW = $00000004
#IDCMP_MOUSEBUTTONS  = $00000008
#IDCMP_MOUSEMOVE    =  $00000010
#IDCMP_GADGETDOWN    = $00000020
#IDCMP_GADGETUP      = $00000040
#IDCMP_REQSET        = $00000080
#IDCMP_MENUPICK      = $00000100
#IDCMP_CLOSEWINDOW   = $00000200
#IDCMP_RAWKEY        = $00000400
#IDCMP_REQVERIFY     = $00000800
#IDCMP_REQCLEAR      = $00001000
#IDCMP_MENUVERIFY    = $00002000
#IDCMP_NEWPREFS      = $00004000
#IDCMP_DISKINSERTED  = $00008000
#IDCMP_DISKREMOVED   = $00010000
#IDCMP_WBENCHMESSAGE = $00020000  ; System use only
#IDCMP_ACTIVEWINDOW  = $00040000
#IDCMP_INACTIVEWINDOW= $00080000
#IDCMP_DELTAMOVE     = $00100000
#IDCMP_VANILLAKEY    = $00200000
#IDCMP_INTUITICKS    = $00400000
; for notifications from "boopsi" gadgets 
#IDCMP_IDCMPUPDATE   = $00800000  ; new for V36
;for getting help key report during menu session  
#IDCMP_MENUHELP      = $01000000 ; new for V36
; for notification of any move/size/zoom/change window
#IDCMP_CHANGEWINDOW  = $02000000 ; new for V36
#IDCMP_GADGETHELP    = $04000000 ; new for V39

Any of the above can be used in an AddIDCMP() function to assign new
IDCMP events to your window. They can also be OR'd together for use in
the flags parameter of Window. Plus they can be used to check the return
from WaitEvent. Thus:

Select WaitEvent
  Case #IDCMP_CLOSEWINDOW ; the window wants closing
  Case #IDCMP_MENUPICK ; menu selected
  Case #IDCMP_NEWSIZE ; someone changed the window size.
End Select

All the above information, and a darn site more, can be found in the
official
autodocs and includes. Theblitz version of the includes also has this
information
in it. Look in include/intuition/intuition.bb2

 CE> Someone once told me "If a program is properly commented, a competent
 CE> programmer in any language should be able to duplicate the program just
 CE> from the comments".

Exactly, and this kind of thing adds to the comment level no end. It helps
to follow the program flow, even if you are looking at a different language.

Simon Archer (Veteran Blitz user)




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.245" "Further c2p notes"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 22 Jul 98 17:39:05 +0000
Subject: Further c2p notes

Hi.

In addition to what I said about the c2p I realised already, I must
also add that the routine is mainly designed for 040 and 060 cpu's,
because of the way it uses caches. 030's have a `writethru' cache
which writes to memory as and when you ask it to, but 040+ have a
write buffer which gets copied back (copyback cache) in big chunks,
and it is this that the c2p makes use of. The c2p will run on all
cpu's but is mainly an 040-to-060 routine.

--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
