Date: 27 Jul 98 20:18:45 +0000
From: "Andy Macklin" <andy@toadhall.u-net.com>
Subject: Re: FindScreen...
X-No-Archive: Yes

Curt typed some of the following:
/<snip>/

> Well, if there is a task named "GoldED" it should be found.  But the
> spelling and capitalization must be exactly the same.  Also, if the program
> was run from a CLI it doesn't seem to work.  Sometimes programs are run as
> "processes" instead of "tasks", although I don't know what the difference
> is.

> For example, if you click on MultiView's icon, you can use
> FindTask_("MultiView") to confirm that it is running.  But if you open a
> shell, and type "SYS:utilities/MultiView", now it won't be found.  Beacuse
> the task is now "CLI (whatever) SYS:utilities/MultiView"...

> This command is really not the best way to do this, but it is the only way I
> have been able to figure out how to use.  The other idea about starting from
> the workbench screen and checking each screen would be a more reliable way
> to do this.

> You would still need to have the exact screen name.

Taken from one of my programs:

---8<---
FindScreen #Project0Scr  ; Screen 0 is the front screen
*s.Screen= Peek.l(Addr Screen(#Project0Scr))   ; Get system structure of Screen
w.l= *s\NextScreen         ; Get address of next screen
While w.l <> 0              ; Screen exists?
*w.Screen= w.l            ; Put pointer to window address
  If UCase$(Peek.s(*w\Title))=UCase$(pubscr$)  ;Is it what we want?
    pubscr$=Peek.s(*w\Title)
    CloseScreen #Project0Scr
    FindScreen #Project0Scr, pubscr$
  End If
  w.l= *w\NextScreen        ; Get address of next screen
Wend
ShowScreen #Project0Scr
--->8---

i.e pretty much what has been suggested. Of course, you could make it more
robust by looking for a string within the screen title.

Andy
