@NODE "Mail.251" "Re: FindScreen..."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 26 Jul 1998 23:25:52 -0500
Subject: Re: FindScreen...

Hi Chris,

On 25-Jul-98, AMIG4@aol.com wrote:
> for some reason FindTask_("name") won`t work either!
> 
>   Task$="GoldED"
>   If FindTask_(Task$)
>      NPrint "Task: "+Task$+" Found!"
>      FindScreen 1,Task$
>   Else
>      NPrint "Couldn't Find Task!"
>   Endif
> 
>   But, no matter what I do, it won't find the task!  When I take the
> FindTask_() part out, it finds the screen because it's definitely open
(GoldED
> is the correct taskname).  Any further ideas?

Well, if there is a task named "GoldED" it should be found.  But the spelling
and capitalization must be exactly the same.  Also, if the program was run
from a CLI it doesn't seem to work.  Sometimes programs are run as "processes"
instead of "tasks", although I don't know what the difference is.

For example, if you click on MultiView's icon, you can use
FindTask_("MultiView") to confirm that it is running.  But if you open a
shell, and type "SYS:utilities/MultiView", now it won't be found.  Beacuse the
task is now "CLI (whatever) SYS:utilities/MultiView"...

This command is really not the best way to do this, but it is the only way I
have been able to figure out how to use.  The other idea about starting from
the workbench screen and checking each screen would be a more reliable way to
do this.

You would still need to have the exact screen name.

I used Xopa from Aminet to find the exact names of screens and tasks, etc.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





