@NODE "Mail.254" "Re: FindScreen"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 18:21:51 -0500
Subject: Re: FindScreen

Hi Chris,

On 24-Jul-98, AMIG4@aol.com wrote:
> Hi,
>   I'm using the command FindScreen 1,"DPaint" to find the screen called
> DPaint.  However, if the screen cannot be found, I get a runtime error
saying
> "Can't Find Screen!".  If I disable the Runtime Errors, my Amiga crashes!
>   I want to know how I can check to see if the screen exists and then use
> FindScreen to allocate it a number.  Any ideas?

Well, there are really 3 problems to overcome here.  Using Xopa, I find that
the task name of Dpaint is "Dpaint", as you would expect.
So, you can use:

If FindTask_ ("Dpaint")
;  (Do the screen-finding)   
EndIf

to determine if it is running.

If it is running, it's safe to use Findscreen to find it's screen.

Problem 2: The Dpaint screen is NOT named "Dpaint", but rather some unreadable
characters.  Does anybody know what the name of Dpaint's screen is?

Problem 3: Dpaint's screen is NOT public. It is a custom screen. It might be
dangerous (or impossible) for you to open any windows on it.


Later...
-- 
Anybody can win, unless there happens to be a second entry.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.255" "FindScreen"
Date: 25 Jul 98 17:02:13 GMT
X-Plug: Xenolink, No. 1 BBS Software for the Amiga!
From: bml@darkside.demon.co.uk (Simon Archer)
Subject: FindScreen

On 24 Jul 98 AMIG4@aol.com wrote about 'FindScreen'.

 Aac> "Can't Find Screen!".  If I disable the Runtime Errors, my Amiga
 Aac> crashes!

You have to be carefull here, the Screen title is not the same as the
screen name. If you use MCP's screen's menu function, you'll see that
this displays the screen's NAME rather than it's title. This is what
you need to pass to FindScreen.

In order to check for a specific screen, you could traverse the screen
list. Or you could alternatively use LockPubScreen() but this will
probably throw up the same as FindScreen. I'm sure they are effectively
the same command anyway.

       Grab the workbench screen.
       Get it's structure
    -->The first long word will be a pointer to the next screen in the list
    |  Check this isn't the screen you want.
    ---If it isn't grab the next screen and start again.

Simon Archer




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.256" "File Notification"
Date:	Sun, 12 Jul 1998 14:29:29 -0300 (ADT)
From:	John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
Subject: File Notification


I'm trying to set up notification on a file/directory so I'll get a 
message when a file is changed.  But for some reason, the StartNotify_() 
function keeps returning 0.  Has anyone ever done this before or can 
anyone see what I'm doing wrong?  

Thanks in advance!


----- Here's The Code -----

test.s = "RAM:"

*mp.MsgPort=CreateMsgPort("Newfiles")

If *incstruct > 0

  *incstruct\nr_Name = &test
  *incstruct\nr_Flags = #NRF_SEND_MESSAGE  ; 1 = message , 16 = initial 
message
  *incstruct\nr_Stuff\nr_Msg\nr_Port = *mp

  If StartNotify_(*incstruct) > 0
    Repeat
      VWait
      result = WaitPort_(*mp)
      If result<>0 Then BeepScreen 0
    Until Joyb(1)<>0
  Else
    result=Request("Info","Notification request failed!","Ok")
  EndIf
Else
  result=Request("Info","NotifyRequest struct failed!","Ok")
EndIf

