@NODE "Mail.269" "Edit$ editfrom editexit"
 Sat, 18 Jul 1998 20:12:22 +0100 (BST)
 (nobody@max02-120.enterprise.net [194.72.197.120])
 <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sat, 18 Jul 1998 10:58:38 +0100 (BST)
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 1998 10:54:19 +0000
From: Oliver Marks <oly@enterprise.net>
Subject: Edit$ editfrom editexit

Hi,

I have written a small text editor using the edit$ command but was
wondering if there is any way to stop the editing if another window is
activated or the current one is deactivated the code i have so far is
included below.


 Use Window 1
  Repeat
  Repeat
    ev.l=Event
    Select ev
    End Select
  Until ev=0
  WLocate 24,y*8+4           ;position of text
  EditFrom x                 ;causes the edit function to end
                             ;if a non character key is pressed
    html$(y)=Edit$(html$(y),linelength);edit text
    x=Editat                 ;starting position of cursor
    Select EditExit          ;test which key was pressed
      Case 13                ;enter pressed
        x=0:If y<20 Then y+1 ;move down a line
      Case 28                ;cursor up 28
        If y>1 Then y-1      ;move up a line
      Case 29                ;cursor down 29
        If y<20 Then y+1     ;move down a line
    End Select
  Until EditExit=27          ;exit if escape was pressed
  Activate 0

All help will be greatfully recieved



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.270" "Re: Disable windows"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 18:34:33 -0500
Subject: Re: Disable windows

Hi All,

On 23-Jul-98, Peter Thor wrote:

> Have you tried *RTLockWindow* and *RTUnlockWindow*?
> If not, do so (I donno if they work though (not on the miggy)).

Yes, these work OK.  Needs to use the Reqtools library, of course.

> I've also got an example code on how to do it in another way, actually its
> Curt Esser's but I'm sure he might write a note about it =) (cheers Curt =)

Well, you beat me to it.  No problem, and actually it was something someone
else had passed along to me!

The difference between these methods is that the RT commands completely lock
the window(s) they are used on.

The OS method only puts up the busy pointer (you can still press gadgets,
etc.)
So with this, you will have to disable the gadgets, menus, etc yourself (if
desired).

About the "invisible requester" method - I never tried this, but maybe a 1x1
requester would work instead of 0x0?  I have used "invisible" 1x1 windows
before.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





