@NODE "Mail.294" "Coding VisualBasic(Blitz3?) for the Amiga."
From: "Jon Lennart Berg" <aniwiese@online.no>
Subject: Coding VisualBasic(Blitz3?) for the Amiga.
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 1998 11:15:52 +0200

This is a multi-part message in MIME format.

------=_NextPart_000_01BDB562.169C33C0

Dear Blitzers.

I posted a message on this group a few days back, telling you that was
working
on a visualbasic clone. I am.
However, many of you seem to think that this will effectively be
Blitzbasic, and that
you can even use the BlitzBasic libraries. I wish i could do that, but
since my
name is not Simon Armstrong, and since i dont have the Blitz assembler
code,
i cant use that.

What i can do, is code the engine for handling objects(Gui elements), and a
script
translator/virtualmachine compiler, link these to an VisualBasic editor (so
you
can draw the GUI).
The limitations however (as i have stated before) is that you will need an
external
program to actualy execute your programs. This is ofcource a simple thing,
just
plog the runner in your C: folder and set it as a tooltype.

I anyone knows how to use Blink with compiled BlitzBasic code, and Xref'ing
to
it from the inside, then, we could create a compiler that makes stand-alone

code.

The script compiler i have made, compiles text scripts (Read:source code)
into
bytefiles. This is the same tecnique that the Java compiler does for its
Virtual
Machine.

I hope that everyone thinks long & hard on how complex this task is, and
that
until we find a way to Blink data and Blitz2, there realy are only one
option, the
bytefile approach.

If you have successfully linked code & data, then please contact me as soon
as
possible.


I also stated in my last letter, that i would not develope the VBA for
Amiga right
now, im working fulltime on my new AmigaOS front-end, called CircleOS, and
until that is finished, we have plenty of time to prone away errors and
find solid
ideas and ground to stand on.
I will release the sourcecode for free, so that every Blitzer can join this
project.

Hope to hear from all of you soon.
Jon Lennart Berg.
------=_NextPart_000_01BDB562.169C33C0
