@NODE "Mail.296" "Re: Coding VisualBasic(Blitz3?) for the Amiga."
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 23 Jul 98 15:14:11 +0000
Subject: Re: Coding VisualBasic(Blitz3?) for the Amiga.

>   Can`t your VisualBasic generate a source file then get blitz to compile that.
>   The BSS had a little control bar window with it so you could compile by press
>   a button ( there were other functions also ).
>   Away it did this using Arexx I think so maybe your VisualBlitz could generate
>   source and send it to blitz automatically.

I think some people are forgetting that Microsoft (puke, vomit,
disgust) Visual Basic has a fully useable sourcecode section. When I
last used it the visual part was like a gui creator with loads of
attributes and stuff, but if you wanted to fiddle about with
sourcecode level modifications you had to do it in the normal way.

I think all refences to Visual Basic should be BANNED.

I think we should take it a stage further and instead of just having
gui-creation we should have a visual code generator as a direct
replacement for the source-code level, flexible to the extent that no
sourcecode is needed to be typed or adusted at any time. Perhaps
something along the lines of the Bars And Pipes music software. Little
icons for instructions and other icons for little macros of
instructions. Representations of loops and conditions and branches and
so on in a graphical way so that you can SEE the program graphically
rather than as text, or with an absolute minimum of text. Then at the
end it passes the generated blitz sourcecode to the editor for
compilation or heaven's forbid finetuning or optimisations.

Better still, how about a direct connection to the mind with a
visualisation interpreter. Hmm, maybe not.

I think a graphical programming language environment would be nice.
Little pictures instead of words, where possible. Easy drag and drop,
cut and paste. Easier visualisation of ideas with multiple macro/micro
levels. Code primitives. Compilation could be called rendering!

hmm

--
Paul.

