@NODE "Mail.299" "Re: CMAP"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 26 Jul 1998 23:07:01 -0500
Subject: Re: CMAP

Hi Alex,

On 26-Jul-98, Dermot Smyth wrote:

>  They
> don't even explain what a "CMAP" file is!

A CMAP is really a "chunk" contained in any .iff picture file, which stores
the colour info.

Blitz apparently saves just this "chunk" without any of the rest of the .iff
header information.  So it is only useful in a Blitz program.

Paint programs actually save palettes as an iff "picture", size 0x0, complete
with a standard .iff header.

So you did the right thing by saving a bitmap with palette.  Just make it as
small as possible, like 16x1.

You could also try saving a 1x1 shape (or possibly even a 0x0) - I never tried
this)

Last, (and most complicated), you could make a routine to write your own .iff
header, complete with size and CMAP info.

And no, I have no idea how to do it that way  ;)

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.300" "CMAP"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 27 Jul 98 14:58:48 +0000
Subject: CMAP

This is a MIME encoded multipart message. The fact that you are reading
this means you don't have a MIME capable mail program. You might still
be able to read part of the mail's content, but some of it may require
a MIME capable mail reader to decode. Following are some URLs where
you can find MIME-capable mail programs for common platforms:

  Amiga............: MicroDot-II  http://www.vapor.com/
