  http://www.cis.ohio-state.edu/hypertext/faq/usenet/mail/mime-faq/top.html

--=_=8<==MD235BC95A8-41AC4A0A==8<=_=

Alex,

I have dug out a few examples of loading IFF files and particularly
ILBM `CMAP' chunks (colourmaps).

I also took a look at some Personal Paint palette files compared with
blitz palette files.

Personal paint seems to save BMHD chunks in its palette files, which
are BitMapHeaDers, which tell it size info and stuff. It probably
relies on that to get the `depth' parameter from which it can work out
the number of colours. Blitz on the other hand seems to save only the
CMAP chunk and uses the `chunksize' parameter which is part of the
chunk to determine how many colours to load.

The two are therefore incompatible.

Blitz saves IFF CMAP chunks, it does NOT produce IFF files! It lacks a
header string which should read "FORM....ILBM" for a start.

You can, as you've found, save an iff picture with the palette
attatched. That will load into ppaint. I suggest you then load the iff
file into a decent text editor. Look for the keyword "CMAP". Then
there will follow some garbage looking data. After that there will be
another 4-byte string. Perhaps CAMG, or BODY, or CRNG. You can cut the
entire file contents from that point onwards including the 4
characters.

All you want in your palette files is the first 12 bytes which are in
the form of FORMnnnnILBM (nnnn is some wierd number). Then the BMHD
chunk, then the CMAP chunk.

Please find attatched two iff files. The first one is in its normal
state and the second is how it will look once you've cut the
unnecessary data to make your ppaint and blitz compatible palette
file.

Why cant you just load your iff picture into ppaint and save the
palette from there anyway?

Incidentally, deluxe paint when saving palettes also saves BMHD chunks
along with its CMAP chunks.

Blitz palette objects are not valid IFF files.

---
Paul.

