@NODE "Mail.308" "chunky cls"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 28 Jul 98 01:27:34 +0000
Subject: chunky cls

Hi.

Many people who want to use chunky graphics, with a c2p routine for
AGA, can now benefit for a special way of clearing the screen. It is
often a feature of chunky games, except for perhaps 3d games, that the
screen needs clearing at some stage. Normally you can write a chunky
clearscreen routine which works quite fast. But it is possible to gain
naughty speed increases by doing the clearscreen as part of the chunky
to planar routine. IOW, while the c2p routine is using an input
address such as move.l (a0)+, you can utilise that address and do a
quick output of zero's. It is as though the clearscreen and the c2p
are sharing an addressing mode.

For example, in the c2p code there might be a line such as:

move.l  (a0)+,d0
move.l  (a0)+,d1
move.l  (a0)+,d2
move.l  (a0)+,d3

etc.

You can implement a quick clearscreen as follows:

move.l  (a0),d0
move.l  a7,(a0)+
move.l  (a0),d1
move.l  a7,(a0)+
move.l  (a0),d2
move.l  a7,(a0)+
move.l  (a0),d3
move.l  a7,(a0)+

You get the picture. The c2p routine is going to be doing a (a0)+
somewhere anyway, and usually you'd have something similar in the cls.
So by combing the two, you cut out a bunch of addressing time. Also
because you are reading from the same address twice, the address will
be in cache and this is what also speeds it up.

You can gain about 25% speed increase by doing this.

If this sounds complicated, it isn't, but I am going to do versions of
my c2p routines with clearscreen implemented. They will be available
at my website shortly.

--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
