@NODE "Mail.327" "Re: c2p notes"
	(envelope-from rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    22 Jul 98 09:11:21 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 1998 09:11:04 +0100
Subject: Re: c2p notes

On 21 Jul 98, at 21:38, Paul West gave this nugget of information:

> So basically if you use it you have to have a fixed size throughout
> your program. Of course, you can duplicate the routine and call it
> something else for another specif dimension, with a little bit of
> search and replace for the constants. Not terribly good coding though.

 Unfortunately (from a simplicity of programming point of view) this 
is where a lot of speed can be found in games - writing your own 
specific routines. For example, if you know you are only ever going 
to Blockscroll at a fixed size, you might as well write your own 
routine to do it and don't include any size bounds checking either 
(fixed size = no problem).


.oO_David_McMinn_Oo.
|rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk|



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.328" "c2p notes"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 21 Jul 98 21:38:52 +0000
Subject: c2p notes

hi

A few notes about the c2p routine I released yesterday.

Firstly, and I only just realised this, you have to specify the
operation's width and height have in constants before the program is
run, rather than being passed to the statement at runtime. This means
you will have a _fixed_ screen dimension for your c2p usage throughout
your program.

Some other c2p routines place width and height into data registes at
runtime and so it is possible to make them variable. But the c2p I
have released uses what's called `Immediate data', in which the
information is passed as `constant' type variables.

I have checked and there are no spare data or address registers in
which to place size info. Also due to the nature of the c2p, in its
special use of caches, it would be terribly unwise to have the size
info read from a memory location.

So basically if you use it you have to have a fixed size throughout
your program. Of course, you can duplicate the routine and call it
something else for another specif dimension, with a little bit of
search and replace for the constants. Not terribly good coding though.

There's nothing I can do about this. But hopefully for most uses,
which will almost exclusively be for games and demos, having a fixed
screensize will not matter. If you are planning to use chunky you will
no doubt be using chunky blitting routines, chunky pixel plotting, and
so on, which you will have to write yourelf (as part of the choice of
using chunky) or get some from somebody/somewhere else.

For my own uses I am using this c2p with a screensize of 320x240 and
will use that throughout the game, inclusive of status panels and
menus and options and title screens and whatever else. For that kind
of approach this c2p is fine.

I will have a harder look to see if I can find a way of introducing
variability but don't hold your breath.

Regards,


--
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
