@NODE "Mail.336" "Re: Byte Type"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 24 Jul 1998 18:13:32 -0500
Subject: Re: Byte Type

Hi Peter

On 24-Jul-98, Peter Thor wrote:
> Hi Blitz'rs.
> 
> Been having a small problem here.
> I'm working with a colourtable and what that table needs to have is the
> colourvalues stored in a byte type format (0-255 actually). Though we know
> that .b can hold a value from +-128 which is VERY annoying.
> 
> Is there a way of overcoming this?

Yes, a .b really CAN hold 0-255.  Turn off overflow errors in your debugger,
as Blitz assumes that you are only using +/-128 and will incorrectly report an
error.
Also, if you need to read these bytes back and use them later in the program,
you must convert and store them into words, or use the "AND $FF" each time you
use them.

a.b=212
nprint a         ; (will give an incorrect negative value)
nprint a AND $FF ; (will give correct value)
aa.w=a AND $FF
nprint aa        ; (also gives correct value)

BTW, the same trick will work for unsigned words, using "AND $FFFF" to
convert.



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.337" "Re: Byte Type"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 28 Jul 1998 21:14:25 -0500
Subject: Re: Byte Type

Hi Peter,

On 28-Jul-98, Peter Thor wrote:
> The 27-Jul-98, Curt Esser wrote:

>> NPrint a.b AND $FF  ;converts for unsigned byte value
> 
> Just what I needed, thanx =)

This also works for using unsigned words - just use " AND $FFFF"
                   
                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.338" "Re: Byte Type"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 27 Jul 1998 15:35:51 -0500
Subject: Re: Byte Type

Hi Centro

On 25-Jul-98, Centro Amiga wrote:

> This is kinda weird. Back when i had Blitz2, the original disk edition you
only had
> to disable overflow checking and Blitz would accept unsigned values as well
> as signed. You can check it on page 22/23 of the manual. But i just tried
out
> this little piece of code:
> 
> a.b=200
> NPrint a.b
> 
> and it spits out -56. I was puzzled. The only explanation i can find is that
> right now i have a new Blitz. The one that i have installed now is the one
> from the Ultimate Blitz Basic 2.1 CD Edition. Maybe there were some
> changes from one release to the other?

No, it is storing the value correctly. It is just not reading it back
correctly.  Blitz always thinks you are using signed bytes, so it reads the
other bit as being a "+" or "-" sign, rather than part of the number.

Just do this to get always the correct answer:

NPrint a.b AND $FF  ;converts for unsigned byte value

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
