@NODE "Mail.350" "bug"
From: "Paul West" <paul@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Date: 31 Jul 98 17:16:57 +0000
Subject: bug

Hi.

I'm really pissed off because there is a really stupid bug or
something going on in my current program. It's a slight modification
of one of the c2p example programs. No alterations to any assembler
but just some extra blitz instructions.

It seems that the order in which you place instructions determines
wether the bloody program will run properly or not!

Sometimes I get a screen opening but it seems like it has no bitmap
attatched whereas if I place certain additional commands in another
place, just a straightforward rearrangement that doesn't influence
what the program actually does, the dam thing works.

I just tried adding a couple of simple lines to load in a couple of
files from disk. It works if I place it before my screen opening
section but not if I place it afterwards. If I take the code out it
works again. I have tried runtime errors they report nothing. The
actual program runs every time but wether it does what it's meant to
do is another matter entirely.

I tried adding a little section of code to create a table of values
but it stopped the screen from seemingly to display anything other
than a default bitmap with title bar. Yet if I moved the code to
another place, which has absolutely no effect on the eventual outcome,
the program seems to work properly.

This is really pissing me off because it should not happen. The code
in a state which actually works is as follows. See the end for further
comments. I even had to move the first InitBank to the start of the
program from where it used to be because it wouldn't work otherwise!!

blitzprogram
; Setup
Gosub table
InitBank 1,#scrwidth*#scrheight,$10000 ; Fastram chunky buffer
InitPalette 0,256
For c=1 To 255 : AGAPalRGB 0,c,Rnd(255),Rnd(255),Rnd(255) : Next c
AGAPalRGB 0,0,0,0,0
VWait
InitBank 0,(#scrwidth*#planeheight)+1000,2|65536 ; Chipram planar buffer
CludgeBitMap 0,#scrwidth,#planeheight,8,Bank(0)
Screen 0,0,0,#scrwidth,#planeheight,8,0,"c2p test",0,0,0
Use Palette 0
VWait 50

; chunky shape
InitBank 2,#objwidth*#objheight,$10000 ; chunky shape
For o=0 To (#objwidth*#objheight)-1
  Poke.b Bank(2)+o,Rnd(255)
Next o

; chunky mask
InitBank 3,#objwidth*#objheight,$10000 ; chunky mask
For o=0 To (#objwidth*#objheight)-1
  If Peek.b(Bank(2)+o)=0 Then Poke.b Bank(3)+o,$ff Else Poke.b Bank(3)+o,$0
Next o

; Do the c2p test
c2p040onlyinit{#scrwidth,#scrheight}
VWait 20
Forbid_
VWait
If #objtype=1
  ResetTimer
  For time=1 To 800
    For cs=1 To #objcount
      chunkyshape1{Bank(2),Bank(1),Rnd(#scrwidth-#objwidth-4)&#objxalign,Rnd(#scrheight-#objheight-4)}
    Next cs
    c2p040only{Bank(1),Bank(0)} ; Convert chunky to planar
  Next time
  t=Ticks
Else
  If #objtype=2
    ResetTimer
    For time=1 To 800
      For cs=1 To #objcount
        chunkyshape2{Bank(2),Bank(1),Rnd(#scrwidth-#objwidth-4)&#objxalign,Rnd(#scrheight-#objheight-4)}
      Next cs
      c2p040only{Bank(1),Bank(0)} ; Convert chunky to planar
    Next time
    t=Ticks
  Else
    If #objtype=3
      ResetTimer
      For time=1 To 800
        For cs=1 To #objcount
          chunkyshape3{Bank(2),Bank(3),Bank(1),Rnd(#scrwidth-#objwidth-4)&#objxalign,Rnd(#scrheight-#objheight-4)}
        Next cs
        c2p040only{Bank(1),Bank(0)} ; Convert chunky to planar
      Next time
      t=Ticks
    Else
      If #objtype=4
        ResetTimer
        For time=1 To 800
          chunkyshape4{Bank(2),Bank(3),Bank(1),Bank(5)}
          c2p040only{Bank(1),Bank(0)} ; Convert chunky to planar
        Next time
        t=Ticks
      EndIf
    EndIf
  EndIf
EndIf

VWait 2 : Permit_
VWait 20
FindScreen 0
Window 0,0,11,640,100,0,"Test results for c2p",0,0
WindowOutput 0
per.f=1/(t/800)
NPrint "Routine performed @ ",50/(t/800),"fps - ",t," ticks - ",per," per frame"
NPrint " "
NPrint "Press mousebutton..."
Free Screen 0
MouseWait
Free Window 0
End

table
; movement table
InitBank 5,#objcount*8,$10000 ; table
For o=0 To (#objcount-1)*8 Step 8
  Poke.w Bank(5)+o,4+Rnd(#scrwidth-#objwidth-12)
  Poke.w Bank(5)+o+2,4+Rnd(#scrheight-#objheight-12)
  xmove.b=Rnd(8)-4
  ymove.b=Rnd(8)-3
  Poke.b Bank(5)+o+4,xmove
  Poke.b Bank(5)+o+5,-xmove
  Poke.b Bank(5)+o+6,ymove
  Poke.b Bank(5)+o+7,-ymove
Next o
Return


This program works. If, however, I remove the `table' subroutine and
just put it in the code prior to the c2p040onlyinit{} call, the
program will run but it will not display my bitmap, and yet displays
the screen titlebar with the titlebar text in it. If I try to put the
code at the start of the program where the gosub is it doesn't work
either, nor does it work if I put it after the Screen instruction or
even just before it after the CludgeBitmap. And yet, the bloody thing
works if I take out the table code or I put a single Gosub in to call
it. The Screen instruction is meant to use bitmap 0. Sometimes it
does, sometimes it doesn't.

I tried putting other code in also and it does the same thing. With
some code it works and some code it doesn't. Does it have anything to
do with alignment of the statement call? Some problem with Bank(n) or
banks generally? It's really annoying because an error like this that
is not due to the program code itself should not occur. I had to move
the first InitBank from where it used to be, just before the
c2p040onlyinit{}, because it made the display error in that position
and seemingly in any other position too except at the start of the
program. If I make much of a modification to the chunky shape
initialisation it cocks up as well.

I tried putting some cache flushes in but that did absolutely nothing.
I just don't understand why it should work when the instructions go in
a certain order but not when in a different order. That's NOT how the
language is meant to work when the order of instructions has no
bearing on what the program does.

Any ideas would be much appreciated.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk




