@NODE "Mail.423" "Re: $VER string bug"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 31 Jul 1998 16:10:28 -0500
Subject: Re: $VER string bug

Hi,

On 31-Jul-98, OPi^Plastic! wrote:

> I add some executable file to my prog <by incbin>,
> If i do version c:myprog i go version this included file :(
> I try to put VER$ string in meany places and it still dosen't
> work :((
> 
> HEEEEEELP!

You can fix like this:

Look in your incbin file with a hex editor until you find the characters
"$VER". This is what the Version command is looking for.  So change this to
something else, like "$XER" - now Version command will pass this and find your
version.

Note: There are also a couple of Blitz libraries in "Otherlibs/" drawer that
have version strings in them.  Test for this with "Version" command, and when
you find them change them the same way.  Now "Version" should always find your
version.

Later...
-- 
Nothing is fool-proof to a sufficiently talented fool.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.424" "Re: $VER string bug"
	(envelope-from rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    31 Jul 98 15:59:48 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 31 Jul 1998 15:59:40 +0100
Subject: Re: $VER string bug

On 31 Jul 98, at 10:15, OPi^Plastic! gave this nugget of information:

> I add some executable file to my prog <by incbin>,
> If i do version c:myprog i go version this included file :(
> I try to put VER$ string in meany places and it still dosen't
> work :((

 It must be due to where blitz places all its data. I think that all 
strings are at the end, which would appear to be after incbins 
judging from your problem. You could try putting the VER$ in as a 
DC.B statement, before the Incbin, i.e.

DC.B "VER$: Blah",0
Even
Incbin "moreblah"


.oO_David_McMinn_Oo.
|rsdm@eee.rgu.ac.uk|



@ENDNODE
